ce:section.ce:para:
Under optimal examination conditions, the effectiveness of the reaction between BSN-CDs and pepsin was thoroughly investigated. Factors such as temperature, reaction time, and pH were systematically varied and monitored to assess their impact on the reaction efficiency and overall outcome. Detailed observations and measurements were recorded to comprehensively understand the interaction between BSN-CDs and pepsin under these optimized conditions. As illustrated in Fig. S2a, the fluorescence signals of BSN-CDs progressively diminished with increasing temperature. The influence of time, ranging from 0 to 7 min, was assessed and depicted in Fig. S2b. Additionally, the effect of pH, spanning from 1.5 to 7 in Gly-HCl buffer, was evaluated as shown in Fig. S2c. Based on these evaluations, it can be concluded that the optimal conditions for detecting pepsin using BSN-CDs are a temperature of 25 °C, a reaction time of 1.5 min, and a pH of 2.5 following the addition of pepsin. A series of pepsin concentrations from 0.0 to 140 µg/mL was tested to establish a fluorometric detection technique for pepsin sensing. As revealed in Fig. 4
                        a, the FL intensity of BSN-CDs exhibited notable changes at various pepsin concentrations. Specifically, the FL signals of BSN-CDs progressively increased with rising pepsin concentrations. An effective linear relationship was detected between the relative FL intensity and pepsin concentrations (Fig. 4b), Y = 0.0355Cpepsin(µg/mL) + 0.0250, R2 = 0.9967). This method demonstrated an exceptionally low detection limit (LOD) of 0.24 µg/mL. These findings verify that this technique is effective for the measurable analysis of pepsin, offering high sensitivity and a broad detection range. Additionally, pepsin levels in patients with GERD varied from 0.003 to 22 μg/mL [52]. The detection limit of BSN-CDs for pepsin was as low as 0.24 μg/mL, demonstrating that BSN-CDs are effective for rapidly detecting pepsin in the saliva of GERD patients. Furthermore, compared to other pepsin fluorescent investigations (Table 1
                        ), BSN-CDs have a larger linear range, lower detection limit, and a quicker response time.
